Overdetermined Linear System of Equations

Consider the following system of mm linear equations in nn variables. a11x1+a12x2++a1nxn=b1a21x1+a22x2++a2nxn=b2 am1x1+am2x2++amnxn=bm,a11x1+a12x2++a1nxn=b1a21x1+a22x2++a2nxn=b2 am1x1+am2x2++amnxn=bm,

  • The system could be represented in a compact form as Ax=bAx=b, where A= a11a12a1na21a22a2nam1am2amn ,x= x1x2xn ,b= b1b2bm A=(a11a12a1na21a22a2nam1am2amn),x=(x1x2xn),b=(b1b2bm)

  • The solution of a linear system represents the point of intersection of hyperplanes given by the lienar equations.

  • The solution also represents the linear coding of the columns of a matrix AA to get a vector bb in the column space (C(A)C(A)).
x1 a11a21am1 +x2 a12a22am2 ++xn a1na2namn = b1b2bm x1(a11a21am1)+x2(a12a22am2)++xn(a1na2namn)=(b1b2bm)

or simply as x1A:1+x2A:2++xnA:n=bx1A:1+x2A:2++xnA:n=b

  • The system is called...

    • a square system when m=nm=n. Admits a unique solution only when AA is invertible.

    • an overdetermined when m>nm>n.

    • an underdetermined when m<nm<n.

Question Pick up all the correct statements

A. Commonly, an over-determined system does not have any solutions.

B. No over-determined system has any solution.

C. An underdetermined system has infinite many solutions.

Least Square Problems (LSP)

When m>nm>n the number of variables is less than the number of equations. These systems are rarely exactly solvable. However, in an approximate sense, we would like to find a vector AxAx in the column space of AA which is closest to bb. In such a case, we aim to find xx such that the residual vector r=bAxr=bAx as small as possible.

LSP Formulation For ARmnARmn (where mnmn) and bRmbRm, find the vector xRnxRn that minimize minimizexRnAxb22minimizexRnAxb22
Why should we use l2l2 norm and not some other norms such as l1l1 or ll norm?
The function is differentiable in l2l2 norm. Moreover, orthogonal transformations could be used as l2l2 norms are invariant under multiplication of the vectors by orthogonal matrices. This leads to better numerical solutions.

Please note the equivalent formulation of the minimizer as

^x=argminxRn(bAx)T(bAx)x^=argminxRn(bAx)T(bAx)

Note that from our discussion on matrix calculus and optimization, the gradient of the above function was found to be AT(Axb)AT(Axb) which also leads to the normal equations discussed ahead.

Theorem

The vector xRnxRn minimizes the residual norm, r=bAx2r=bAx2, if and only if rcol(A)rcol(A).

It follows from the above theorem that rcol(A)rN(AT)rcol(A)rN(AT) as column space and left-null space are orthogonal.( Recall C(A)N(AT)=RmC(A)N(AT)=Rm. ) This implies that ATr=0AT(bAx)=0ATAx=ATbATr=0AT(bAx)=0ATAx=ATb

Which naturally leads us to the normal equations ATAx=ATb.ATAx=ATb. Note, the computation above attempts to demonstrate how the normal equations solve the LSP problem by minimizing the residual norm.

The condition number of rectangular matrix BB of rank rr could be given by (B)=1(B)r(B)(B)=1(B)r(B)

The condition number for the systems of normal eqaution thus comes out to be (ATA)=212r=[(A)]2(ATA)=12r2=[(A)]2

Theorem

For ARmnARmn (where mnmn) and bRmbRm, if the vector xRnxRn satisfies the condition ATAx=ATbATAx=ATb, then xx solves the least square problem.

3x+2y=32x+3y=0x+2y=1(1)(2)(3)(1)3x+2y=3(2)2x+3y=0(3)x+2y=1

Connection with Projection

When the solution of the LSP (in full column rank case) is ^x=(ATA)1ATbx^=(ATA)1ATb, the projection of vector bb onto the column space of AA is A^x=A(ATA)1ATbAx^=A(ATA)1ATb. So, the projection matrix that projects vector bb onto the column space of AA is given by ^H=A(ATA)1AT,H^=A(ATA)1AT, and the residual, ^r=bA^x=(I^H)br^=bAx^=(IH^)b.

Full Rank LSP Solutions

When AA is full column rank, the matrix ATAATA is invertible and the normal equations coudl be solve simply (or naively) by ATAx=ATbx=(ATA)1ATbATAx=ATbx=(ATA)1ATb

Solving LSP by using Cholesky Decomposition

It follows that ATAATA is a symmetric positive semi-definite matrix. Therefore, once our normal matrix has been constructed, we can apply Cholesky decomposition to further simplify our least square problem. In fact, the use of Cholesky decomposition allows the original problem to be stated in a way that is efficiently solved by numerical solutions.

Theorem: Cholesky Decomposition For any real positive-definite matrix BRnnBRnn, there exists a qnique lower triangular matrix LRnnLRnn so that BB is decomposed as B=LLTB=LLT.

In LSP, if the matric AA is full column-rank, ATAATA is symmetric positive defintie and satisfies the conditions for Cholesky decomposition ATA=LLTATA=LLT. It follows that ATAx=ATbLLTx=ATbATAx=ATbLLTx=ATb

By letting LTx=zLTx=z, we can solve the following system by forward substitution Lz=ATbLz=ATb

Once we have solved for zz, we can finally solve for xx by backward substitution LTx=zLTx=z

Note: The order of floating point operations is O(13n3+mn2)mn2+13n3flopsO(13n3+mn2)mn2+13n3flops


Solving LSP using QR Decomposition

Theorem: QR Decomposition

For any matrix ARmnARmn, there exists an orthogonal matrix QRmmQRmm and an upper triangular matrix RRmnRRmn so that AA is decomposed as A=QRA=QR.

Thin (Economy) QR For any matrix ARmnARmn, A=Q1R1A=Q1R1 where matrix Q1RmnQ1Rmn is an orthonormal column matrix and R1RnnR1Rnn is an upper triangular matrix.

Solving LSP by using SVD

In the case of a full column-rank matrix AA, the economy SVD could be given by A=U(n)(n)VTA=U(n)(n)VT, where U(n)U(n) is made of the first nn columns of UU (from full SVD). Please note that the dimensions of these matrices are mnmn, nnnn and nnnn respectively.

The projection matrix that projects AA onto the column space of AA could be given by P=U(n)UT(n)P=U(n)U(n)T as the columns of U(n)U(n) provide an orthonormal basis for the column space of AA. There for xx is such that Ax=PbAx=Pb. This implies
U(n)(n)VTx=U(n)UT(n)bUT(n)U(n)(n)VTx=UT(n)U(n)UT(n)bU(n)(n)VTx=U(n)U(n)TbU(n)TU(n)(n)VTx=U(n)TU(n)U(n)Tb
It should be noted that UT(n)U(n)=InU(n)TU(n)=In, so we have the equivalent system

(n)VTx=UT(n)bx=V1(n)UT(n)b(n)VTx=U(n)Tbx=V(n)1U(n)Tb


The number of floating point operations in this approach is 2mn2+11n3flops2mn2+11n3flops

SVD and Rank-deficient (multi-collinear) LSP

When the matrix AA in the LSP is not full-rank, the normal equations have infinitely many solutions. Let be the set of all such solutions ={xRn:ATAx=ATb}={xRn:ATAx=ATb}

Can you prove that the set of all such least square solution is a convex set?

Our aim is to find the unique LSP solution that has the smallest l2l2 norm. We will denote it by xLSxLS. SVD provides the approach to find such a solution.

Theorem Let the SVD of rank rr matrix ARmnARmn, be given by A=ri=1iUiVTi,A=i=1riUiViT, in the outer product form, then the `smallest' least square solution to the LSP is given by xLS=ri=1(UTibi)VixLS=i=1r(UiTbi)Vi and the minimum residual norm is obtained by 2LS=mi=r+1(UTib)2.LS2=i=r+1m(UiTb)2.

The proof of the above follows from the fact that
Axb22=UVTxb22=VTxUTb22=zUTb22Axb22=UVTxb22=VTxUTb22=zUTb22
where z=VTxz=VTx. Then the expression on the right could be expressed as
  1z1rzr00 UT1bUTrbUTr+1bUTmb   22=   1z1UT1brzrUTrbUTr+1bUTmb   22=ri=1(iziUTib)2+mi=r+1(UTib)2 (1z1rzr00)(U1TbUrTbUr+1TbUmTb) 22= (1z1U1TbrzrUrTbUr+1TbUmTb) 22=i=1r(iziUiTb)2+i=r+1m(UiTb)2
Clearly, the above expression will admit the minimum value mi=r+1(UTib)2i=r+1m(UiTb)2 only when the first expression is zero, implying that zi=UTib/izi=UiTb/i for i=1:ri=1:r. In addition, the smallest x2x2 norm will require zi=0zi=0 for i=r+1:ni=r+1:n. Therefore,
x=Vz=ri=1ziVi=ri=1(UTibi)Vix=Vz=i=1rziVi=i=1r(UiTbi)Vi

Pseudoinverse and LSP

We defined pseudo-inverse when we studied SVD. Here is the definition again for all to recall.

Pseudo-inverse (Moore-Penrose Inverse)

The pseudo-inverse of a rectangular matrix ARmnARmn of rank rr, whose SVD is given by A=UVTA=UVT, is a unique rectangular matrix A+RnmA+Rnm, given by

A+=V+UTA+=V+UT

where +=diag(11, 12, , 1r, 0, , 0)Rnm+=diag(11, 12, , 1r, 0, , 0)Rnm

It turns out from above that the calculation of smallest least square solution in the case of rank-deficient LSP could actaully be performed by the pseudo-inverse as
xLS=A+bandLS=bAxLS2=bAA+b2=(IAA+)b2xLS=A+bandLS=bAxLS2=bAA+b2=(IAA+)b2

We have at different occassions proved several properties of pseudo-inverse. Here are some of them

  • When m=n=rank(A)m=n=rank(A), the pseudoinverse is the inverse: A+=A1A+=A1.

  • When AA is full row-rank, m=rank(A)m=rank(A) and A+=AT(AAT)1A+=AT(AAT)1 is the right inverse of AA.

  • When AA is full column-rank, n=rank(A)n=rank(A), A+=(ATA)1ATA+=(ATA)1AT is the left inverse of AA.

  • The matrix P=AA+P=AA+ is an orthogonal projection onto column space C(A)C(A).

  • The matrix P=A+AP=A+A is an orthogonal projection onto row space R(A)R(A).

The pseudoinverse is the unique minimal solution to the problem minimizeXRnmAXIF.minimizeXRnmAXIF.

Variants for LSP

Weighted Least Square Problems

^x=argminxRn(bAx)TW(bAx)x^=argminxRn(bAx)TW(bAx)

where WW is a diagonal matrix of non-negative weights that assigns weights to different observations in the least square formulation.

Generalized Least Square Problems

^x=argminxRn(bAx)T1(bAx)x^=argminxRn(bAx)T1(bAx)

where is the covariance matrix for the data.


Can you show that the formulation of the generalized LSP is equivalent to the follwing constrained problem. minimize vTvsubject to b=Ax+1/2vminimize vTvsubject to b=Ax+1/2v

Column-weighted Least Square Problems If we scale the columns of the matrix AA then the LSP computes the solution of minimizezRn(AG1)zb22minimizezRn(AG1)zb22


Such scaling is common place, for example, in normalization of features of a data-matrix such as G=G2:=diag{A12,A22,,An2}G=G2:=diag{A12,A22,,An2} It has been shown that with this choice of the scaling, the condition number (AG1)(AG1) is approximately minimized that affects the accuracy of zLSzLS. However, some orthogonalization based methods may not return the same estimate (see p.307 Golub).

Regularized LSP

In ridge regression, we solve an optimization problem in the following form minimizexRnAxb22+x22minimizexRnAxb22+x22 where the ridge-penalty is chosen to shape the solution in some desired way.

Can you show that the normal equations for this problem is given by (ATA+I)x=ATb(ATA+I)x=ATb

One clear advantage of using this regularization is that it takes care of the near rank-deficiency (multicolliniarity) of AA as ATA+IATA+I could be made invertible by choosing appropriately. See Golub (p 307-308) on how could be chosen in an optimum way.


Follow the SVD of A=UVTA=UVT method discussed earlier to show that (T+I)VTx=TUTb(T+I)VTx=TUTb and hence x()=ri=1iUTib2i+Vix()=i=1riUiTbi2+Vi

In Tikhonov regularization problem, we solve an optimization problem in the form minimizexRnAxb22+Bx22minimizexRnAxb22+Bx22 where BRnnBRnn.

Can you show that the normal equations for this problem is given by (ATA+BTB)x=ATb.(ATA+BTB)x=ATb.
